{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017T97s3YZPSPM3JkeKHvwsY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture of the spark-pi namespace configuration. Let me analyze what I found:\n\n**RBAC:**\n- `spark-pi` ServiceAccount: exists, dedicated SA (good)\n- `default` ServiceAccount: also exists but not bound to the role\n- Role `spark-pi-role`: grants permissions on `services`, `configmaps`, `persistentvolumeclaims`, AND `pods` (verbs: create, get, list, watch, delete, update, patch)\n  - According to the rollback-rehearsal configmap, the original role only had `[\"services\", \"configmaps\", \"persistentvolumeclaims\"]` — `pods` was added as a non-default change\n- RoleBinding `spark-pi-role-binding`: binds `spark-pi` SA to `spark-pi-role`\n\n**Deployments (spark-master and spark-worker):**\n- Image: `apache/spark:3.5.3` (no digest pinning — uses mutable tag)\n- Resources set (both): requests cpu=200m/mem=512Mi, limits cpu=500m/mem=1Gi\n- Security context is empty at both pod and container levels, missing critical hardening like `runAsNonRoot`, `readOnlyRootFilesystem`, and privilege escalation controls\n- ServiceAccount: `spark-pi` (dedicated SA — good)\n- `imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent` — doesn't force fresh pull (could use cached image)\n\n**Job (spark-pi):**\n- Image: `apache/spark:3.5.3` (same tag, no digest)\n- Resources set: same as deployments\n- Security context: empty\n- RestartPolicy: `Never` (good for jobs)\n- ServiceAccount: `spark-pi`\n- Status: completed successfully\n\n**Network Policies:**\n- None defined in the namespace\n\n**Key findings:**\n\n**COMPLIANT (what's correctly configured):**\n1. Dedicated ServiceAccount `spark-pi` created and used by all workloads (master, worker, job) — NOT the default SA\n2. RBAC Role `spark-pi-role` scoped to namespace (no ClusterRole)\n3. RoleBinding correctly binds `spark-pi` SA to `spark-pi-role`\n4. Resource requests AND limits set on all containers (master, worker, spark-submit job): cpu/memory both set\n5. Image pinned to a specific minor version tag `apache/spark:3.5.3` (not `latest`)\n6. Job uses `restartPolicy: Never` (appropriate for batch jobs)\n7. Job completed successfully (backoffLimit: 0, succeeded: 1)\n\n**GAPS / FINDINGS:**\n1. **RBAC over-permission**: Role `spark-pi-role` includes `pods` resource with full create/get/list/watch/delete/update/patch — the rollback script confirms this was added beyond the original intent. The `pods` permission allows workloads to create/delete arbitrary pods in the namespace, which could be exploited.\n\n2. **No container security context on any workload**: All containers (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit job) have empty security contexts at both pod and container level. Missing critical settings like `runAsNonRoot`, `readOnlyRootFilesystem`, and `allowPrivilegeEscalation: false`.\n\n3. **Image not pinned to digest**: All three workloads use the mutable tag `apache/spark:3.5.3` rather than a digest-pinned reference, which provides no provenance guarantee and leaves the image vulnerable to tampering.\n\n4. **No NetworkPolicy**: The namespace has zero network policies, so all pods can communicate freely with each other and across namespaces without any least-privilege restrictions.\n\n5. **imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent combined with mutable tags**: This means Kubernetes will reuse whatever image version is already cached on the node, bypassing any security checks or updates.\n\n6. **No namespace-level LimitRange or ResourceQuota**: While individual pods have resource limits, there's no namespace-wide cap to prevent a compromised pod from spawning new containers up to node capacity.\n\nNow I'm identifying what was correctly configured from the original setup — the resource limits on deployments and jobs, the dedicated ServiceAccount, and the RBAC role scoped to specific resources — versus the gaps like missing security contexts, network policies, and image digest pinning. I'll compose the findings and create the ConfigMap to document these issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1111,"cache_read_input_tokens":33756,"output_tokens":2936,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1111,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":2936,"cache_read_input_tokens":33756,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1111,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1111},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":{"applied_edits":[]}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4d03e86-f82f-4b87-8820-0ca6f15e92e8","uuid":"632848c0-e9c4-4247-a757-000000000000","request_id":"req_011CcLNv8uiFtGoZWYoA5uuN"}
